• Talking about the lasso today
  • Great tool for variable selection
  • reduces overfitting
  • an extension of a linear model

\[ \min_{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^{p+1}} \left[ \frac{1}{2N} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - x_i\beta \right)^2 + \lambda ||\beta||_{1} \right] \]

  • An optimization problem
  • sum of absolutes of beta
  • could also do ridge
  • focusing on lasso

  • just the blue diamond
  • not differentiable

theFormula <- Sale_Price ~ Longitude + Latitude + 
  Lot_Frontage + Lot_Area + Street + Utilities +
  Bldg_Type + Overall_Qual + Year_Built + Foundation + 
  Exter_Cond + Heating + Central_Air + 
  First_Flr_SF + Second_Flr_SF + Full_Bath + Half_Bath + 
  Kitchen_Qual + TotRms_AbvGrd + Garage_Type + 
  Garage_Cars + Open_Porch_SF + Pool_Area + Fence
  • still need a formula
  • including many predictors
  • save as variable for reuse
  • Sale_Price as outcome
  • put this into recipes

basic_rec <- recipe(theFormula, data = ames_train) %>%
    # collapse some levels into "other"
    step_other(all_nominal(), threshold = 0.01) %>%
    # remove variables with zero variance
    step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% 
    # center and scale numeric variables
    step_center(all_numeric()) %>% step_scale(all_numeric()) %>% 
    # turn categoricals into dummies, don't drop baseline
    step_dummy(all_nominal(), one_hot=TRUE) %>%
    # ensure there is an intercept
    step_intercept()
  • start recipe with formula
  • add steps: zero variance, center and scale
  • don’t drop the base line for dummies, not worried about colinearity
  • add intercept, not all functions add it automaticaly

prepped <- basic_rec %>% prep(training=ames_train, retain=TRUE)

Quadratic Programming

  • because why not?

\[ \min_{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^{p+1}} \left[ \frac{1}{2N} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - x_i\beta \right)^2 + \lambda ||\beta||_{1} \right] \]

  • back to our loss function
  • will remove the constant divider

\[ \min_{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^{p+1}} \left[ ||Y - X\beta||_2^2 + \lambda||\beta||_1 \right] \]

  • matrix notation
  • unconstrained quadratic optimization
  • \(\lambda\) is a Lagrange multiplier

\[ \min_{\beta \in \mathbb{R}^{p+1}} ||Y - X\beta||_2^2 \\ \text{subject to } ||\beta||_1 \le t \]

  • constrained quadratic optimization
  • \(t\) is inversely proportional to \(\lambda\)

\[ (Y - X\beta)^T(Y - X\beta) \\ (Y^T - \beta^TX^T)(Y - X\beta) \\ Y^TY - Y^TX\beta - \beta^TX^TY + \beta^TX^TX\beta \\ Y^TY - 2Y^TX\beta + \beta^TX^TX\beta \\ Y^TY+ \beta^TX^TX\beta - 2Y^TX\beta \]

  • rewrite the loss function
    • transpose, expand and FOIL
  • some matrix rearranging

\[ \min_{x} \frac{1}{2} x^TVV^Tx + c^Tx \\ Ax = b \\ l \preceq x \preceq u \]

  • sparse quadratic optimization
  • \(\preceq\) is nondomniated symbol
  • in optimization \(x\) is unknown, in stats \(\beta\) is unknown

\[ \min_{\beta^+, \beta^-} \left[(\beta^+ - \beta^-)XX^T(\beta^+ - \beta^-) - 2YX^T(\beta^+ - \beta^-) \right] \\ \text{subject to } \sum_{j=1}^p (\beta^+ - \beta^-) \le t \\ \beta^+ \succeq 0, \beta^- \succeq 0 \]

  • rewrite to solve over \(\beta^+\) and \(\beta^-\)
  • beta positive, beta negative
  • because \(q = q^+ - q^-\)
    • q is equal to its positive part minus its negative part
  • allows for far fewer constraints than \(2^p\) otherwise needed

lasso.qp <- function(x, y, t)
{
    y <- as.vector(y)
    p <- ncol(x)
    # get negative and positive side of X
    Vn <- x %*% cbind(diag(p), -diag(p), 0)
    # compute YX
    YX <- colSums(x * -y)
    Zn <- c (2*YX, -2*YX, 0)
    # get upper bound for coefficients
    mod <- lm.fit(x, y)
    # replace any NAs with the maximum of all coefs
    b_ols <- mod$coefficients %>% replace_na(max(mod$coefficients, na.rm=TRUE))
    # create matrices and vectors
    u <- c(abs(b_ols), abs(b_ols), sum(abs(b_ols)))
    A <- matrix (c(rep (1, 2*p), 1), nrow=1)
    b <- c(min(t, sum(abs(b_ols))))
    # solve
    soln <- LowRankQP::LowRankQP(Vmat=sqrt(2)*t(Vn), dvec=Zn, Amat=A, 
                                 bvec=b, uvec=u, method="LU")
    return(round(soln$alpha[1:p] - soln$alpha[(p+1):(2*p)], digits=5))
}
  • a lot of housekeeping to get it in quadratric programming form
  • positive portion minus negative portion
  • adapted from Erik Drysdale: http://www.erikdrysdale.com/l1_solution/

# train matrices
x_train_dense <- prepped %>% 
  juice(all_predictors(), composition='matrix')
y_train_dense <- prepped %>%

mod_keras <- keras_model_sequential() %>%
    layer_dense(units = 1, activation = "linear", 
                kernel_regularizer=regularizer_l1(l=0.02),
                input_shape = dim(x_train_dense)[2])
  • one layer with linear activation
  • linear model
  • regularizer_l1 is lasso
  • solve for coefficients with stochastic gradient descent

mod_keras %>% compile(

  • notice modification in place
  • rmsprop: adaptive learning rate optimizer

history <- mod_keras %>% 
    fit(
        x=x_train_dense,
        y=y_train_dense,
        epochs = 30,
        batch_size=64,
        validation_split = 0.1,
        view_metrics=TRUE,
        callbacks=list(
            callback_early_stopping(monitor='val_acc',
                                    patience=10),
            callback_reduce_lr_on_plateau(monitor='val_loss',
                                          factor=0.1,
                                          patience=5),
            callback_tensorboard("logs/run_lasso")
        )
    )
  • input, output
  • 30 passes over data
  • batch_size: fewer is better
  • learning rate

plot(history)

  • more training gets closer to better results
  • a few seconds on this laptop running on battery
  • do again for each lambda
  • glmnet can do hundreds in a second

# test matrices
x_test <- prepped %>% 
  bake(all_predictors(), composition='matrix', new_data=ames_test)
y_test <- prepped %>% 
  bake(all_outcomes() ,composition='matrix', new_data=ames_test)
predictions <- list(
  glmnet=predict(mod_glmnet, newx=x_test, s=0.0004),
  xgboost=predict(mod_xgboost, newdata=x_test[, mod_xgboost$feature_names]),
  lars=predict(mod_lars, newx=x_test, s=50)$fit,
  stan=predict(mod_stan, newdata=stan_recipe %>% 
                 bake(new_data=ames_test, composition='tibble')),
  quad=x_test %*% mod_quad,
  keras=predict(mod_keras, x=x_test)
)
predictions <- predictions %>% 
  map(~data.frame(Pred=as.numeric(.))) %>% 
  map_df(. %>% mutate(Actual=as.numeric(y_test)) %>% mutate(.Resid=Actual-Pred), 
         .id='Model')
  • bake test data
  • make predictions for each model
  • bake seems to change the order of the columns
  • slightly different interface for each model

ggplot(predictions, aes(x=Actual, y=Pred, color=Model)) + 
  geom_abline(color='grey50', linetype=2) + geom_point(alpha=1/2, shape=1, size=1) + 
  geom_smooth() +facet_wrap(~Model) + theme(legend.position='none')

  • turn it into one data.frame
  • dashed line is perfect predictions
  • Stan and xgboost

error_measures <- predictions %>% 
  group_by(Model) %>% summarize(RMSE=sqrt(mean(.Resid^2))) %>% 
  arrange(RMSE) %>% mutate(Model=reorder(Model, RMSE))
ggplot(error_measures, aes(x=Model, y=RMSE)) + geom_col(width=0.5, fill='lightblue')

  • stan won: learned best lambda
  • xgboost second: not true model
  • keras last
